Guardians of the Shrine of Eilistraee, these drow are capable warriors.

Fiercely sought after by certain trackers and wardens, these helms possess horn-shaped ear cones that amplify the wearer's hearing tenfold. While the materials used in creation offer little in terms of protection to the face, it offers an unrivaled advantage when it comes to aural detection.

Its a well known fact that elves are foppish gits, barely able to lift their own swords without a limp-wristed floppy motion. It was for this very reason that these boots were forged. 

The master elven smith Yaldriirmathileh Mastiiramaeviil, spent many long hours making these boots for the elven protectors of the long forgotten court of Myth Drannor. When the kingdom fell, many of these boots were lost, some fell into the hands of those responsible for the fall, others are a prized possession from a dragons hoard. 

Perhaps the adventurer who has stumbled upon them now will use them to serve their intended purpose. Perhaps though, they have simply made another step along the road to obscurity.
A polished golden shield set with a large gemstone that seems to act as a third eye for the shield holder, allowing them to see more than most with a conventional tower shield.
The tower shield is a veritable wall of protection, though it can be quite cumbersome to carry on an adventure.

The magically enhanced drow piwafi cloak is one of the most important accoutrements of a drow's possession. Even the most common of these cloaks carries a most powerful enchantment to protect its wearer. All drow long to own a piwafi; though, only those who have proven themselves useful, or who come from rich, powerful families can afford to own one.

Crafted with care by the reclusive and little known sea-elves, these rings are a simple silver band wrought in a somewhat waving pattern, clasping two twin blue pearls. Each pearl is enchanted to help the wearer hear and see in the depths of the murky ocean, as well as the ring itself providing some minor magical fortification.
A copy of an amulet identifying one as Sutrinos, an elite leader of the Melee-Magthere.  These amulets are only worn by commanders that have proven their worth time and time again to the academy.

This old worn tome writen in undercommon is a quintessential guide to underdark cooking. Within its pages are indeed 1001 recipies using fungus, moss and lichen native to the Underdark. 

Some recipies of note include:

Ripplebark Soup - Taking the slave out of slave soup!

Barrelstalk - Not just for construction anymore!

Fire Lichen - Goes with everything!

Brown Mold - Dangerously delicous!

Shrieker - Screamingly good to eat!

Not to mention over 200 varities of mushroom soup recipies.
1001 Ways to Cook Fungus, Mold and Lichen

A book to help drow learn common or for others to learn drow. It contains translations for common words and useful phrases such as "Please dont kill me, I'm not your enemy",  "Where is the latrine?" and many others

Xas - Yes
Nau - No
Naut - Not
Vendui - Hello
Aluve - Goodbye

An uplifting collection of short stories and poems writen by dark elves who have escaped the Underdark's reaches, battled the demons in their own hearts and proven themselves better than their dark kin. Though many of the names are kept confidential, one might note that the hand writing of many of the poems matches members past and present of the Shrine of Eilistraee.

"The moon's lamentations fall upon us each eve as she rises. She weeps for us for she loves us and cannot bear the wickedness the webbed lies of her mother weaves around so many of our souls. Yet, we brave few who see the truth stand together as the dark elves and true children of the night."
Ripplebark Soup for the Drow Soul

Eilistraee's Dogma

Aid the weak, strong, grateful, and churlish alike. Be always kind, save in battle with evil.

< On Promoting Joy >
Encourage happiness everywhere; lift hearts with kind words, jests, songs, and merriment. Whenever possible, food should be eaten with accompaniment of song. Except for properly sad occasions, a feast should be accompanied by merriment. Promote happiness and gaiety whenever possible.

< On Self-improvement >
Learn how to cook game and how best to hunt it. Learn how to play, make, and repair musical instruments. Learn new songs, dances, and ways with weapons, spices, and recipes, and pass this learning on whenever possible. Practice music and swordwork.

< On Possessions >
Wealth is to be used to buy food, musical instruments, good swords and armor, and other tools to serve the will of the goddess. When on the road feed, aid, and defend the needy along the way with a prayer to the goddess. Lend assistance to those who fight for good, asking as price no more than an object that can be used to the benefit of the goddess' works.

< On Food >
Where food cannot be purchased or received, it must be gathered or hunted for. Feed yourself by your own gardening and hunting skills as much as possible. Set aside food and give it as often as possible to strangers in need, particularly outcasts and those of other races. In times of plenty, store food for lean times ahead.

< On Strangers >
Strangers are your friends. Any hungry travelers met with, who offer no threats, are to be fed--carry food at all times for this purpose. The homeless must be given shelter from storms, under your own roof if need be. In harsh winters, patrol the lands about to find and take in the lost, the hurt, and those caught in the teeth of cold. Try to convert at least one stranger per moon to the worship of Eilistraee.

< On Conflict >
Defend and aid all folk, promoting harmony between the races. When fighting evil burn the bodies of the evil creatures slain as an offering to the goddess--unless such creatures are edible and non-sentient, and there are hungry folk near. When faithful and allies fall in battle, any priestess present must, if possible, provide burial, a funeral song, and comfort to the bereaved. Repay rudeness with kindness. Repay violence with swift violence, so that the fewest may be hurt and danger fast removed from the land.

< On Drow >
Aid all drow who are in distress. If the drow are in combat the fighting is to be stopped with as little bloodshed as possible. So long as the drow met with are not working evil on others, they are to be aided and given the message of Eilistraee: A rightful place awaits you in the Realm Above, in the Land of the Great Light. Come in peace and live beneath the sun again, where trees and flowers grow.

< This is the credo of the Dark Maiden. >
The flavor and texture of these mushrooms make them a popular part of most drow pantries.
These mushrooms are notable for their sweet, candy-like flavor, and are often used in drow cuisine in place of sugar.
Lengths of mint leaves hung up to dry, for making tea and use in other dishes.
These ferns are a common dish in some parts of Faerun.  They're quite tasty when harvested fresh, and cooked with a bit of butter.
A painting of an Eilistraeen priestess, possibly one of the Shrine's founders.
A lantern of obvious drow origins.  Looking at the craftsmanship, especially the spider motif, it's a fair guess that this was stolen or retrieved from some Llothite settlement.
Lantern Retrieved from Udos Dro'Xun's Ruins
A large crystal that looks like amethyst, except for the fact that it sheds pale light and energy, both in the visual spectrum and that seen by darkvision, as well as a soft, musical humming noise.

This spice chest, if opened, seems to contain a large collection of exotic underdark spices. There's several different varieties of rare, ground mushrooms, powdered boiler eel heat gland, and dried, powdered venoms, amongst other things.
This pool seems to be lined with moonstone, and is filled with holy water. Several bottles filled with the divine substance sit nearby.
An armoire containing comfortable robes to wear after ceremonies have been performed.

These thin, silvery robes bear the holy symbol of the Dark Maiden in tasteful silver embroidery on them.  They are cut to be loose and flowing, so as not to impede the wearer's movements in the slightest.

A drow-styled chest made of stone. Opening it, you'd see several folded, glowing robes inside.
These moth-eaten garments are little more than a short tunic after years of storage.  The brightly luminescent belt is now better served as a collar, however...
